pe":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance","Chloramphenicol drops","Surgical excision","Mitomycin C","Voriconazole eye drops"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPterygium is a type of conjunctival degeneration. It is associated with sun exposure. It appears as a vascular sheet of tissue growing from the nasal or temporal conjunctiva and may cross the limbus and grow over the cornea. Pterygium can cause irritation which may be relieved by lubricating eye drops and avoiding sun exposure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical excision\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if it is causing significant discomfort for the patient, if it is causing decreased vision by inducing astigmatism or if the patient is finding it cosmetically unacceptable. It should be noted that there is always a risk of recurrence after surgical excision which should be clearly communicated to the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated if the patient is not bothered by it and it is not causing any corneal distortion or decreased vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloramphenicol drops\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Evoriconazole eye drops\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this case as it is not caused by an infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitomycin C \u003C/strong\u003Emay be used at the time of the surgical excision to decrease the risk of recurrence but is not a treatment on its own.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Surgical excision is indicated if a pterygium is causing significant discomfort for the patient, if it is causing decreased vision or if the patient is finding it cosmetically unacceptable."],"references":["Shahraki T, Arabi a, Feizi S. Pterygium: an update on pathophysiology, clinical features, and management. her Adv Ophthalmol 2021; 13: 1\u201321"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"